# {{lb|en|reflexive|now|rare}} To sleep for longer than one intended. {{defdate|from 15th c.}}
#* {{RQ:Richardson Clarissa|letter=81|text=A]fter such a train of fatigue and restless nights, I had unhappily '''overslept''' myself […].}}
#*'''1764''', {{w|Horace Walpole}}, ''The Castle of Otranto'', IV:
#*:Theodore made awkward excuses, and attributed his delay to having '''overslept''' himself.
#*'{{RQ:Grahame Wind in the Willows|passage=The following morning, Toad, who had '''overslept''' himself as usual, came down to breakfast disgracefully late, [...].}}
# {{lb|en|transitive}} To sleep beyond (a given time), to sleep through (an event etc.). {{defdate|from 16th c.}}
#:{{ux|en|to '''oversleep''' one's usual hour of rising}}

